kulangara Devi Temple: The goddess Durga Bhagavathy, an embodiment of Ma Parvati, is worshipped in the Hindu temple Kottankulangara Devi Temple in Chavara. Its distinctive construction, in which the temple has no ceiling above the sanctuary, fascinates tourists. At the Kottankulangara Festival, the only temple in India executes a special ritual in which males dress as women (annual festival). Many young ladies enter the temple at night in a lengthy procession while holding lit lamps, offering payasam, aravana, and iratti madhuram, as well as jewellery, silks, and other items. This special ritual is known as "Chamaya Vilakku." St. Andrews Church, Kovilthottam Beach & Lighthouse, and other attractions can be found in and near Chavara. 21. Thevally Palace: On the shores of Ashtamude Lake stands Trevally Palace, a location of significant historical significance. Its most distinctive feature is the palace's unique combination of Dutch, English and Portuguese architectural traditions. It will take you to the quaintness of the past. The surrounding lush green coconut plantation and palm trees give this palace's splendour a stunning look. One of Kollam's top historical attractions in this architectural marvel. 22. Oachira: The Oachira, a tourist destination recognized for attracting many tourists, is located on the Kollam-Alappuzha route. The famous Parabrahma temple, devoted to global awareness, is the only deity or idol at this well-known pilgrimage site, making it special. The two biggest yearly festivities are Oachira Kali in mid-June and the twelve-day Panthrandu Vilakku in November/December. The Puranas claim that this magnificent temple is among the most respected and well-known locations in Kerala or even the entire nation. 23. Pathanapuram: Pathanapuram is one of the important trading locations in the Kollam District. Pathanapuram, situated on the edge of the river Kallada, is one of Kollam's well-known tourist destinations. The Chandanakkudam Mahotsavam festival, 