ists are entranced by its beauty and tranquillity. 27. Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel Police Museum: The Kerala police forces are honoured, and their history and progress are traced in the Sardar Vallabhai Patel Police Museum. The museum has a statue of Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel, famous as the "Iron Man of India". The Martyrs Gallery, which houses police collections of weapons and ammunition from the 18th and 19th centuries, including bullets, firearms, machines, and much more, is one of this city's most well-known sights. The location also has informational charts on DNA testing, human bones, fingerprints, photographs of police dogs, and untold secrets about the Kerala Police force. The museum is open daily except for Sundays from 9:00 am to 6:00 pm. 28. Chinnakada Clock Tower: The Clock Tower is a well-known landmark in Kollam town and is situated near Chinnakada. The centre of the city of Kollam is recognized as being here. The tower faces the city's four directions and has clocks on every side, attracting tourists because of its unique colonial-era architectural style. The city's busiest area is where the highways from Thiruvananthapuram, Alappuzha, Downtown, Sengottai, Ashramam, Kollam Beach, and the City bus station connect. The clock tower has become a non-official icon of Kollam. 29. Kollam Pooram - Sri Krishna Temple: Every April, Sri Krishna Temple celebrates the well-known 10-day Kollam Pooram festival. The event begins with raising a flag, and the deities of local temples are taken to the Krishna Temple upon 58 gorgeously dressed elephants to offer honour to Lord Krishna. Cherupooram is the name of this ceremony. Every day of the event has a Kathakali performance. The Kudamattam event is luxuriously celebrated on the festival's final day. Thousands of devotees gather on the temple grounds to see this magnificent spectacle. 30. Rosemala: Rosemala is a well-kept secret in Kerala and is kept in the charming, natural forests of the Shenduruney forests. The valley, 