ude creating brooms, boating, using Chinese nets, fishing using catnets, and processing clams. 15. Rameshwaram Temple: This Kollam temple was built in the Pandian style architecture and is believed to have been there since the 12th century. The Natukotta Chettiar, a famous merchant caste and devotees of Lord Shiva, constructed four Shiva temples; this one is one of them. The statue of the mythical monster Vyala is an intriguing aspect of this temple. These inscriptions, which range from the 12th to the 16th century, are written in Tamil on many occasions. Every year in January or February, the annual temple celebration is held. One of Kollam's top tourist attractions is this one. 16. Munroe Island: Munroe Island, 26 kilometres from Kollam and located at the intersection of the Astamudi Lake and the Kallada River, is named after the British resident of Travancore, Colonel Munroe. Munroe Island, sometimes referred to as Mundrothuruthu, is a beautiful and majestic inland island well recognized for its unique beauty and stunning views. This undiscovered gem consists of eight islands in total, each of which is divided by a lake or a tiny waterway. By boat, Munroe Island can be reached from Pattomthuruthu and Pezhumthuruthu Islands. Twice daily boat excursions are offered to the island. It is among the best of the well-known locations in Kollam. 17. Kollam Adventure Park: The vast tourist area famous as Picnic Village has the 200-year-old Government Guest House, an Adventure Park, the Tourism Boat Club, the Children's Traffic Park, and the Yatrinivas. The centre of entertainment for people of all ages is next to the government guest house in the Asramam Picnic Village, also known as Adventure Park. Because of the area's picturesque backwaters, tourists may enjoy picnics, luxury boating, and the art museum in Kollam, among other tourist attractions. The adventure park's major attractions include sculptures, an outdoor gym, a mangrove forest, boating, and a British residency. 18. Kottukkal Cave Temple: On the Thiruvananthapuram-Kottayam MC Road, in the Kotthukkal village, is the stunning and tranquil Kottukkal Cave Temple, a rock-cut sanctuary dedicated to Lord Shiva. Kottukal refers to a carved rock, also known as Kothiya Kallu. In Malayalam, the temple is also referred to as Kaltrikkovil. There are two caverns in this temple, the larger of which contains the Nandi Bull and the smaller one, Lord Hanuman. One can observe the idol of Lord Ganapathy between these caves. The temple, a superb example of the rock-cut building common during the sixth and eighth centuries (CE), is revered by both religious worshipers and historians of design. 19. Paravur Lake: One of the well-known lakes in Kollam is Paravur Lake, also known as Paravur Kayal. The shimmering waters are a wonderful sight. Relatively a small lake, it is a great place for visitors to go for a day trip and enjoy the natural beauty. The mangroves that line the lake's edges increase its beauty and attraction. The Priyadarshini Watercraft Club is another prominent site in the Paravur Lake area. The most popular sports around here are swimming and surfing, followed by fishing, which needs permission from the local government. The Puthenkulam Elephant Village and neighbouring Puttingal Temple are the other top attractions in addition to the waters. 20. Kottankulangara Devi Temple: The goddess Durga Bhagavathy, an embodiment of Ma Parvati, is worshipped in the Hindu temple Kottankulangara Devi Temple in Chavara. Its distinctive construction, in which the temple has no ceiling above the sanctuary, fascinates tourists. At the Kottankulangara Festival, the only temple in India executes a special ritual in which males dress as women (annual festival). Many young ladies enter the temple at night in a lengthy procession while holding lit lamps, offering payasam, aravana, and iratti madhuram, as well as jewellery, silks, and other items. This special ritual is known as "Chamaya Vilakku." St. 