 2. Thangassery Lighthouse: The Thangassery Lighthouse, also known as the Tangasseri Light House, believes to be the second-highest on Kerala's whole shore and is one of the popular tourist destinations in Kollam. As a result, one of the most popular lighthouses in the state. The tower was built in 1902, is 41 meters (135 feet) tall, and has been used ever since. The massive tower stands out and is visible thanks to its painted red and white oblique stripes. It looks wonderful in all its splendour and majesty. Times: 10:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. and 2:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.; closed on Monday. 3. Palaruvi Falls The English name for Palaruvi Waterfalls is "Stream of Milk." The shape of the white-stream waterfall, which is 300 feet in height and flows very rapidly, From June to January is the best time to visit this destination. It is India's 32nd-highest waterfall and is reputed to provide Ayurvedic benefits. It is one of the most popular tourist spots in Kollam because the surrounding forests and mist-covered mountains' peacefulness contrasts dramatically with the fall's thunderous sounds. Times: 8 am to 4 pm. 4. Sasthamkotta Lake: The biggest lake and the first in Kerala is called Sasthamkotta, and a historic Sastha Temple is believed to have given the lake its name. Hills surround the primary source of drinking water for Kollam residents on three sides. The lake water is a freshwater supply because of the larva chaoborus (insect) in the water, which is in charge of eliminating germs from the lake water and making it safe for drinking. There is 27 type of fish that live in the lake. In this lake, you can go swimming and boating. Times: 24 hours, but 10 am to 6 pm is preferable. 5. Kollam Beach: Kollam Beach doesn't need any introduction; it was chosen as Kerala's first "Beach Wedding Destination." There are many things to do in Kollam, but this beach is one of the prettiest and most attractive. This beach, known to some travellers as Mahatma Gandhi Beach, calms travellers 