e time with the creatures of nature? Visit the Shenduruny Wildlife Refuge. One of the best sites to visit in Kollam is in the Western Ghats of Kerala's Kollam district. Only this wildlife sanctuary, known for its vast range of animals and plants and stunning environment, is located in Kollam. It includes bird watching, vehicle excursions, walking, and camping in the bush. The Agasthyamalai biosphere reserve includes the sanctuary, and the sanctuary is located on a 26-square-kilometre artificial lake created by the Thenmala Dam. 13. Punalur: Punalur, one of Kollam's most unique tourist destinations, provides a reviving experience and an Old World charm. Two words in Tamil and Malayalam are the source of the name Punalur. Punalur, which means "place of water," is named after the Tamil word "punal," which means "water," and the Malayalam word "ooru," which means "place." The iconic suspension bridge hangs over the Kallada, which runs directly through the city's centre. The "Pepper Village of Kerala" is Panalur. Shenthruni Forest, Palruvi, Courtallam Waterfalls, and the historic Pattazhi Devi Temple are some of the area's tourist attractions. 14. Kakkathuruthu: The Kakkathuruthu Island in Alleppey's Vembanad Lake is small and beautiful. It is also referred to as the "Island of crows." It's a beautiful place to see birds. Some unique features that make Kakkathuruthu special are coconut trees, paddy fields, toddy tapping, fish farming, coir production, and traditional Kerala cuisines like appam, puttu, crab roast, shrimp fry, duck and hog meals with fresh catch from the backwaters. Additionally, tourists enjoy the sunset and the changing colours of the sky. The only location in Kerala that National Geo magazine recommends for enjoying the sunset. Activities include creating brooms, boating, using Chinese nets, fishing using catnets, and processing clams. 15. Rameshwaram Temple: This Kollam temple was built in the Pandian style architecture and is believed to have been the