eople of all ages is next to the government guest house in the Asramam Picnic Village, also known as Adventure Park. Because of the area's picturesque backwaters, tourists may enjoy picnics, luxury boating, and the art museum in Kollam, among other tourist attractions. The adventure park's major attractions include sculptures, an outdoor gym, a mangrove forest, boating, and a British residency. 18. Kottukkal Cave Temple: On the Thiruvananthapuram-Kottayam MC Road, in the Kotthukkal village, is the stunning and tranquil Kottukkal Cave Temple, a rock-cut sanctuary dedicated to Lord Shiva. Kottukal refers to a carved rock, also known as Kothiya Kallu. In Malayalam, the temple is also referred to as Kaltrikkovil. There are two caverns in this temple, the larger of which contains the Nandi Bull and the smaller one, Lord Hanuman. One can observe the idol of Lord Ganapathy between these caves. The temple, a superb example of the rock-cut building common during the sixth and eighth centuries (CE), is revered by both religious worshipers and historians of design. 19. Paravur Lake: One of the well-known lakes in Kollam is Paravur Lake, also known as Paravur Kayal. The shimmering waters are a wonderful sight. Relatively a small lake, it is a great place for visitors to go for a day trip and enjoy the natural beauty. The mangroves that line the lake's edges increase its beauty and attraction. The Priyadarshini Watercraft Club is another prominent site in the Paravur Lake area. The most popular sports around here are swimming and surfing, followed by fishing, which needs permission from the local government. The Puthenkulam Elephant Village and neighbouring Puttingal Temple are the other top attractions in addition to the waters. 20. Kottankulangara Devi Temple: The goddess Durga Bhagavathy, an embodiment of Ma Parvati, is worshipped in the Hindu temple Kottankulangara Devi Temple in Chavara. Its distinctive construction, in which the temple has no ceiling above the sanctuary, f