. There includes: A theatre. A computerized audio-visual room. A cable car. The Siddha Cave Healing Center. Timings: 30 am to 5.30 pm. In this museum, visitors may utilize virtual reality to study Jatayu's history. Several adventure sports are present, including zip-lining, trekking, rappelling, valley crossing, paintball, laser tag, archery, bouldering, rock climbing, and air rifle shooting. 2. Thangassery Lighthouse: The Thangassery Lighthouse, also known as the Tangasseri Light House, believes to be the second-highest on Kerala's whole shore and is one of the popular tourist destinations in Kollam. As a result, one of the most popular lighthouses in the state. The tower was built in 1902, is 41 meters (135 feet) tall, and has been used ever since. The massive tower stands out and is visible thanks to its painted red and white oblique stripes. It looks wonderful in all its splendour and majesty. Times: 10:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. and 2:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m.; closed on Monday. 3. Palaruvi Falls The English name for Palaruvi Waterfalls is "Stream of Milk." The shape of the white-stream waterfall, which is 300 feet in height and flows very rapidly, From June to January is the best time to visit this destination. It is India's 32nd-highest waterfall and is reputed to provide Ayurvedic benefits. It is one of the most popular tourist spots in Kollam because the surrounding forests and mist-covered mountains' peacefulness contrasts dramatically with the fall's thunderous sounds. Times: 8 am to 4 pm. 4. Sasthamkotta Lake: The biggest lake and the first in Kerala is called Sasthamkotta, and a historic Sastha Temple is believed to have given the lake its name. Hills surround the primary source of drinking water for Kollam residents on three sides. The lake water is a freshwater supply because of the larva chaoborus (insect) in the water, which is in charge of eliminating germs from the lake water and making it safe for drinking. There is 27 type of fish that live in the lake. In this lake, you can go swimming and boating. Times: 24 hours, but 10 am to 6 pm is preferable. 5. Kollam Beach: Kollam Beach doesn't need any introduction; it was chosen as Kerala's first "Beach Wedding Destination." There are many things to do in Kollam, but this beach is one of the prettiest and most attractive. This beach, known to some travellers as Mahatma Gandhi Beach, calms travellers with its lush greenery, peaceful backwaters, and various water sports. The Tangasseri Lighthouse, another prominent feature near the beach, is a lighthouse. The spiritual and cultural atmosphere at the beach is amazing and gives visitors fresh energy and motivation. The timeframe is from 10:00 am to 5:00 pm. 6. Ashtamudi Lake: The words "Ashta," which means "eight," and "Mudi," which means "branch," are combined to form Ashtamudi Lake, a spectacular natural feature in Kerala. This name indicates that the lake has eight branches. It is Kerala's second-largest lake, and There are dense coconut and palm trees along the lake's shoreline. Chinese fishing nets are another well-known feature of the lake's shoreline. On Ashtamudi lake, backwater trips are another choice between Kollam and Alappuzha. The boat ride to the Munroe Islands is a fantastic adventure. Many resorts located around the lake provide a variety of water activities. 7. Thenmala: The Western Ghats' foothills in the Kollam district, recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, are home to Thenmala, India's first planned eco-tourism destination. The name Thenmala translates as Honey Hill. The Parappar Dam crosses the Kallada River and is located in Thenmala. Thenmala forest honey is famous for its medicinal benefits. This location offers attractions such as winding walkways, the Sway Bridge, a theatre, musical fountains, boats, and more. On a mountain railway track to the east is the 13-arched Pathimoonam Kannara Bridge. Thenmala also has Deer Park as an attraction. 8. Mayyand: Mayyanad is one of the top tourist destinations in Kollam since it is the centre of numerous well-known Hindu and Muslim temples and shrines. It is situated along the Arabian Sea's shoreline and the Paravur Lake's shores. It is 10 kilometres from Kollam and home to nine significant temples. The Subramanya temple in Umayanallor, which is reported to have received a blessing from Shri Shankaracharya of Kalladi, is the most significant of the nine temples there. An old mosque and numerous old churches are also available nearby. From Kollam to Mayyanad, buses run regularly. 9. Kumbhavurutty Waterfalls: The Kumbhavurutty Waterfall, one of the well-known tourist attractions in Kollam, located in southern India, is renowned for its crystal-clear blue waters that fall from tremendous heights. The Achankovil River contains a waterfall. The Kumbhavurutty Waterfalls, which are close to the Konni Forest Area, are among Kerala's most magnificent and stunning waterfalls. This beautiful location never fails to mesmerize tourists with its beautiful views and the beauty of the water falling from a height of 25 meters. 10. Sri Mahaganapathi Temple: One of the popular pilgrimage sites in Kollam, this temple is famous among worshippers as a place of devotion and spirituality. Even though Lord Siva is the temple's main god, people often call it the Lord Ganapathy Temple because it is located in Kottarakkara, 25 kilometres from Kollam. The Kottarakkara Unniappam, a rare delicacy served as Prasadam, is the temple's claim to fame. Most visitors are attracted to this centuries-old temple by its attractive architecture. Even non-Hindus are welcome to enter this temple, where the family of Shiva lives, which is one of its most amazing features. 11. Thirumullavaram Beach: An undiscovered beach in Kerala with golden sand surrounding crystal blue water is decorated by coconut and palm trees, creating a quiet and shaded area. The annual Karkidaka Vavubali tradition is what makes this beach so well-known. This beach, on the list of tourist 