ditionally, tourists enjoy the sunset and the changing colours of the sky. The only location in Kerala that National Geo magazine recommends for enjoying the sunset. Activities include creating brooms, boating, using Chinese nets, fishing using catnets, and processing clams. 15. Rameshwaram Temple: This Kollam temple was built in the Pandian style architecture and is believed to have been there since the 12th century. The Natukotta Chettiar, a famous merchant caste and devotees of Lord Shiva, constructed four Shiva temples; this one is one of them. The statue of the mythical monster Vyala is an intriguing aspect of this temple. These inscriptions, which range from the 12th to the 16th century, are written in Tamil on many occasions. Every year in January or February, the annual temple celebration is held. One of Kollam's top tourist attractions is this one. 16. Munroe Island: Munroe Island, 26 kilometres from Kollam and located at the intersection of the Astamudi Lake and the Kallada River, is named after the British resident of Travancore, Colonel Munroe. Munroe Island, sometimes referred to as Mundrothuruthu, is a beautiful and majestic inland island well recognized for its unique beauty and stunning views. This undiscovered gem consists of eight islands in total, each of which is divided by a lake or a tiny waterway. By boat, Munroe Island can be reached from Pattomthuruthu and Pezhumthuruthu Islands. Twice daily boat excursions are offered to the island. It is among the best of the well-known locations in Kollam. 17. Kollam Adventure Park: The vast tourist area famous as Picnic Village has the 200-year-old Government Guest House, an Adventure Park, the Tourism Boat Club, the Children's Traffic Park, and the Yatrinivas. The centre of entertainment for people of all ages is next to the government guest house in the Asramam Picnic Village, also known as Adventure Park. Because of the area's picturesque backwaters, tourists may enjoy picnics, luxury boating, and the